the causes and consequences of ballot order effects siepr siepr stanford institute for economic policy research search the site enter your keywords main links home about siepr research at siepr education at siepr events at siepr people at siepr publications at siepr economics in the news support siepr contact us stay connected stay connected banner home publications profile display the causes and consequences of ballot order effects type siepr discussion paper 06 029 author s marc meredith yuval salant published 02 1 07 download pdf abstract to better understand how list orderings affect choices of economic significance we explore how ballot order affects election outcomes unlike previous work we show that ballot order significantly affects the results of elections in more than five percent of the elections in our dataset of california multi member district local elections the candidate listed first won office as a result of the ballot ordering using multi member district elections allows us to isolate the mechanisms leading to order effects in a way unavailable in single member districts we reject the hypothesis that ballot order effects only result from voters running out of available votes prior to reaching the end of the ballot we also demonstrate that ballot order effects are history dependent candidates perform worse when they are listed immediately after higher quality candidates this suggests that policy makers should use more sophisticated rotation schemes to mitigate order effects finally we find evidence that our point estimates are robust to the presence of partisan cues stanford university economics department stanford center for international development public policy program site map economic summit
